comment_data.body: Is this in public flutter repo source?  (Can we easily set up a comparable project?)

If this is in a package in the flutter repo, you have to open the individual packages in `//packages/` as separate IntelliJ modules. If you just open the entire repo in IntelliJ, there is an IntelliJ project and individual modules already defined.
This is in public Flutter repo. To reproduce, open `dev/devicelab` as an IntelliJ module. Then try navigating from `bin/run.dart` to `package:flutter_devicelab/framework/manifest.dart` import.

I'm able to reproduce this; if I make an edit to the file then I do see navigation start to work. This is using `1.21.0-dev.0.0` of the dart sdk.

@bwilkerson @scheglov
Does the navigation information that server sent IntelliJ include a navigation region for the URI? Is there an error indicating that server couldn't resolve the URI?

@bwilkerson 

Where do I get this information? (assuming the question was directed at me)

I'll take an answer from anyone who has an answer :-)

If you've configured the IntelliJ registry entry `dart.server.additional.arguments` to include a command line argument starting with `--instrumentation-log-file=`, then the file you specified will contain all of the communication between IntelliJ and server. (But only for the current session, so if you've restarted IntelliJ since the problem occurred you'll need to reproduce the bug in order to get the data recorded again.) Search for a line containing the text `"event"::"analysis.navigation"`. There should be a parameter of the form `"file"::"/a/b/c/d.dart", where the file path is the path on your machine to the file containing the URI from which you couldn't navigate. If you can send me that line (in an e-mail, because it might contain sensitive data), that would help.

> If you've configured the IntelliJ registry entry dart.server.additional.arguments to include a command line argument starting with --instrumentation-log-file=

@bwilkerson, @jwren : are there user docs any where for instrumentation?  If not, should there be?

Thanks Jaime!  This doc is great.

@devoncarew @mit-mit : I wonder if we shouldn't update it and publicize it some more?
I think we should convert this to markdown and put in the [sdk wiki](https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/wiki).

Ok. We figured out why this is happening. When analyzer is asked to analyze code in a given directory, it looks in that directory for an analysis options file. If one isn't found, it will look in the parent directory, parent's parent directory, etc. In this case, we find the file in the root of the flutter directory. That file contains the lines

```
exclude:
    - 'bin/**'
```

This means that we won't analyze the file `bin/run.dart`, so we have no information to use to provide navigation.

@Hixie Is this exclude directive needed, or can it be removed?

Is there a way to exclude files from linting but still get analysis for navigation/code-completion purposes? These are two orthogonal aspects, one is for our own productivity, the other is to ensure code quality for our users.

I don't understand the question. I initially assumed you meant that navigation/code-completion is for our own productivity, but I don't understand how excluding files from linting ensures code quality, so I assume I'm not understanding what you're saying.
That exclude is meant to apply to `//bin/cache/` - we should probably just update that exclude.
Yeah that's just supposed to exclude the Dart SDK itself from Flutter's analysis. It shouldn't exclude any files actually in the Flutter SDK.
